"&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWritten evidence from Heathrow Hub Ltd (HSR 028)&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nSubmission by Heathrow Hub Ltd to the Transport Select Committee Follow up inquiry into High Speed Rail&#xa0;1\n9\nth\n November 2013\n&#xa0;\nExecutive Summary&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nIntroduction&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe strategic context&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nHS2’s objectives&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe need for speed&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe lessons of HS1&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe effect of speed – energy consumption&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe effect of speed – noise&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe effect of speed – environmental &#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe effect of speed - cost&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe effect of speed – environmental impacts&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe effect of speed – journey time savings&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nAlternative routes&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nHS2 and airport infrastructure&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nHS2 and related infrastructure&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nConclusion&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nNovember 2013\n&#xa0;\n \nPara 5, Strategic Case for HS2\n \nHM Treasury &amp; Infrastructure UK, October 2010, updated December 2012. \nhttps://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/infrastructure-uk/series/national-infrastructure-plan\n \n \nVehicle technology is advancing quickly, and systems that interact with their surroundings and with other vehicles are becoming increasingly common. These technologies create the opportunity for vehicles that can autonomously manage actions that are currently reserved for the driver and could, in the future, be able to carry out all of the driver tasks. The UK has a fantastic opportunity to be at the forefront of these developments”\n – Para 3.39, Action for Roads, \nCommand Paper Cm 8679, \nDfT\n July 2013 \nhttps://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/212590/action-for-roads.pdf\n \n \n“The Committee repeats its call for the Department to publish a national transport strategy to explain what the Government aims to achieve by spending money on transport and how its policies support these aims. It is now a full year since we first made this recommendation in our report on Transport and Economy so we look forward to hearing more from Ministers on this crucial matter when that report is debated on the floor of the House on 28 February\"\n – Louise \nEllman\n MP, 23\nrd\n February 2012 \nhttp://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/transport-committee/news/scrutiny-of-dft-pn-report-/\n \n“\nWe recommend that a White Paper be published, clarifying the Government’s objectives for all transport spending and the criteria it will use for deciding between different claims on the available resources”\n – Recommendation 5, \nTransport and the Economy, Third Report of Session 2010-12, House of Commons Transport Committee \nhttp://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmselect/cmtran/473/473.pdf\n \n \n“\nIn our report on Transport and the economy we called for the \nDfT\n to publish a strategy to explain what the Government aims to achieve by spending money on transport and how its policies support these aims. The department dismissed our recommendation, pointing us to the lists of actions in the business plan. The business plan is a useful and informative document but it does little more than list transport policies and target dates for implementation. It sits in a strategic vacuum and can easily be overtaken by events\n” -\n \n“Counting the cost: financial scrutiny of the Department for Transport 2011–12, Fifteenth Report of Session 2010-12, House of Commons Transport Committee\n \nhttp://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201012/cmselect/cmtran/1560/1560.pdf\n \n \n“The absence of a transport strategy makes it hard to assess how HS2 relates to other major transport infrastructure schemes, regional planning and wider objectives, such as bridging the north-south divide. The biggest single transport investment proposed in this Parliament should be grounded in a well thought- through strategic framework and we are disappointed that the Government has not developed a strategy for transport, particularly after it rejected our earlier recommendation to publish a White Paper on transport and the economy”\n – \nRecommendation 1, High Speed Rail, Tenth Report of Session 2010-12\n \nhttp://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201012/cmselect/cmtran/1185/1185.pdf\n \n \n“\nAppraisal of alternative options lies outside your brief but is important in the context of allocating the limited funds available for investment in the national transport network” - \nHS2 Ltd Analytical Challenge Panel 17th Dec 2010\n \n“The National Policy Statement on national networks … will set the context in which HS2 will be considered”\n – \npara\n. 1.2.10, High Speed Rail, London to the West Midlands and Beyond, A Report to Government by High Speed Two Ltd. December 2009\n \nhttp://infrastructure.planningportal.gov.uk/legislation-and-advice/national-policy-statements/\n \n \n“A Conservative Government will support proposals along the lines of the plan put forward by engineering firm, Arup, for a new Heathrow rail hub. This would link Heathrow terminals directly into the main rail network and the lines to Reading, Oxford, Bristol, Plymouth, Cardiff, Swansea, Cheltenham and Southampton, greatly improving public transport links to the airport. The plan would also include construction of a new high speed link connecting Heathrow airport to the Channel Tunnel Rail link and the new route north, providing a viable alternative to thousands of short haul flights now clogging up the airport”\n -\n Conservative Rail Review, February 2009 \nhttp://www.conservatives.com/%7E/media/Files/Downloadable%20Files/Railreview.ashx?dl=true\n \n \n“I think that [the Hub] is an attractive idea. It’s vital that we have an integrated approach to planning new rail capacity and any new airport capacity that’s also required”\n – Lord Adonis, Secretary of State for Transport, Sunday Times 4\nth\n January 2009, \nhttp://cma.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/Test/politics/article141091.ece\n \n \nColumn 356, \nhttp://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200809/cmhansrd/cm090115/debtext/90115-0006.htm\n \n“Early tests suggested that reducing journey times by one minute would provide benefits of around £300-600m on a fully \nutilised\n high speed line” \n– p.17, HS2 Demand Model Analysis, HS2 Ltd. February 2010 \nhttp://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20110131042819/http://www.dft.gov.uk/pgr/rail/pi/highspeedrail/hs2ltd/demandandappraisal/pdf/report.pdf\n \np 56 HS2 Demand Model Analysis, HS2 Ltd. February 2010\n \nLetter 13th February 2009 from Sir David \nRowlands\n, HS2 Ltd, to Lord Adonis \nhttp://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/documents/HS2_ObjectivesAndRemitHS22009.pdf\n \n \n“With such a high top speed, there could be no tunnels and few curves. Aerodynamic forces \nwould increase tunnel costs ten\nfold”\n - Andrew McNaughton, Chief Engineer HS2 Ltd, Rail News 1\nst\n June 2009. \nhttp://www.railnews.co.uk/news/business/2009/06/01-hs-two.html\n \nhttps://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/high-speed-two\n \nMinimum radius of curvature 300kph (as HS1 design) 4050m, 400kph (HS2 specification) 7200m, HS2 Technical Standards \nhttp://hs2.xplodelite.com/assets/x/77048\n \n \nReport to Government by HS2 Ltd, December 2009 \nhttp://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/+/http:/www.dft.gov.uk/pgr/rail/pi/highspeedrail/hs2ltd/hs2report/pdf/chapter3a.pdf\n \n \nPara 7.7, High Speed Rail Command Paper, March 2010 \nhttp://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/+/http:/www.dft.gov.uk/pgr/rail/pi/highspeedrail/commandpaper/pdf/cmdpaper.pdf\n \n \n“There should be no intermediate stations between Heathrow International and West Midlands. Intermediate stations\n \nwould lead to significant erosion of average speed”\n - Letter from Sir David \nRowlands\n to Lord Adonis, 13\nth\n February 2009\n \nPara 49, Strategic Case for HS2\n \n“Telling the People’s Daily that speed restrictions would be placed on the trains to make them most cost-efficient, \nSheng\n \nGuangzu\n, head of China’s railways ministry, said that trains running at 350 \nkph\n consume twice as much energy as those traveling at 200 \nkph\n. Slowing them up will save both on power costs and maintenance. Speeds are to be cut back from upwards of 350 \nkph\n to 200 kph-250 \nkph\n with a maximum of 300 \nkph\n” - \nhttp://chinabystander.wordpress.com/2011/04/14/slow-train-coming/\n \n“Other than some detailed design issues, HS1 has fitted into the surrounding countryside well, with few complaints”\n – Getting Back on Track, Campaign to Protect Rural England 2011 \nwww.\ncpre\n.co.uk/resources/transport/item/download/379\n \n \n“Damage to landscape, heritage and \ntranquillity\n must be minimal, \nfor example by running new lines along existing road and rail lines\n wherever possible, as well as extensive \ntunnelling\n, landscaping and noise barriers”  \n- CPRE \nhttp://www.cpre.org.uk/campaigns/transport/rail/highspeedrail\n \n \nhttp://rightlines.org.uk/\n \n \n“On environmental grounds, the new line (between Cologne and the Rhine/Main conurbation) was generally constructed in parallel with an existing motorway, as close to it as possible. For this reason, the maximum gradient was set at 40%, minimum track radius at 3350m and maximum cant at 170mm, which allows a design speed of 300 km/hr around curves.” \n - \nDr.Ing\n. \nEberhard\n \nJaensch\n, Network Strategy Unit, DB \nNetz\n AG, Railway Technical Review 2/05\n \n“\nThe route exploits the natural lie of the land and runs alongside the motorway to \nminimise\n environmental impact … within a corridor with an already dense infrastructure”\n – The\n New High Speed Turin - Milan \nLine, RFI 2005 \nhttp://www.rfi.it/cms-file/allegati/rfi/The%20new%20high%20speed%20TURIN%20-%20MILAN%20line.pdf\n \n“The preferred route of HS2 crosses the Chilterns AONB at its widest point, in contradiction to the policy followed by HS1. In Kent, the route of HS1 was amended to avoid the AONB … and run beside the existing M20, a major strategic transport corridor which reduced incremental noise pollution and landscape damage. By contrast, HS2 appears to have been deliberately routed through the least spoilt, widest part of the Chilterns” \n– Steve Baker MP, Westminster Hall debate 23rd November 2010 \nhttp://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm101123/halltext/101123h0001.htm#10112319000001\n \n“The Chilterns Conservation Board is very concerned that the construction and presence of such a major piece of transport infrastructure would permanently blight the Chilterns. The Board is also concerned that the Chilterns will see no benefits from High Speed 2, since none of its services will stop at local stations, and they might even disrupt trains on the Chiltern Railways network”\n  - Chilterns Conservation Board press release 7\nth\n August 2009 \nhttp://www.chilternsaonb.org/news_detail.asp?ID=133\n \n“The East-West rail link would create an arc of technology and new industry, linking Reading, at the heart of the Thames valley, Science Vale UK with its world-leading research and development facilities, Oxford with its academic and tourism economy, Milton Keynes, Cambridge and East Anglia” \n– Iain Stewart, MP Milton Keynes South, Westminster Hall debate 15\nth\n November 2011 \nhttp://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm111115/halltext/111115h0001.htm#11111553000002\n \n \nhttp://www.andrealeadsom.com/downloads/kent-criteria-for-hs1.pdf\n \n \n\"The engineers say to me the \n(phase 2)\n line should go by the road network”\n \n- \nRt\n Hon Patrick \nMcLoughlin\n MP\n, Secretary of State for Transport, BBC News 1\nst\n February 2013 \nhttp://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-21293724\n \n \nPara 4.10.11, Strategic Case for HS2\n \n“\nJourney time saving of 3.5 minutes consumes 23% more energy (comparison of 360 km/h operation to 300 km/h operation)”- \nHS2 Traction Energy \nModelling\n December 2009 \nhttp://www.hs2.org.uk/assets/x/56774\n \n“The UK is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by at least 80% by 2050, relative to 1990 levels”\n – \nDepartment of Energy and Climate Change\n \nhttp://www.decc.gov.uk/en/content/cms/tackling/2050/2050.aspx\n \n“Demand reductions across all sectors of the economy will be essential” -\n Generating the Future, UK Energy Systems Fit for 2050, The Royal Academy of Engineering March 2010 \nhttp://www.raeng.org.uk/news/publications/list/reports/Generating_the_future_report.pdf\n \n \n“Work was underway to assess balance between power consumption and speed”\n – \nHS2 Ltd. Minutes of Technical Challenge Group 29th April 2009\n \nPara 54, Strategic Case for HS2\n \n“The biggest issue in increasing \nShinkansen\n [high speed train] speed is noise control”\n-\n \nEast Japan Railway Company Technical Review Summer 2008\n \nhttp://www.jreast.co.jp/e/development/tech/contents12.html\n \n \nhttp://www.jreast.co.jp/E/press/20071101/index.html\n \n \nPara 49, Strategic Case for HS2\n \nMetro, 20th March 2011\n - \nhttp://www.metro.co.uk/news/858625-transport-secretary-philip-hammond-only-nimbys-oppose-250mph-trains#ixzz1MK3yQC2k\n \n“Should it be implemented, the current high speed rail proposal could negatively affect the local environment of two areas: the Chilterns (which is an Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty - AONB) and the Vale of \nAylesbury\n and Warwickshire. Paragraph 22 of the Planning Policy Statement 7 (Sustainable Development in Rural Areas) states that major development within an AONB can only be considered if it satisfies the following criteria:1) It is clearly in the national interest and: 2) It cannot be built anywhere else. The Chilterns Conservation Board, an independent body established by Parliamentary Order in July 2004 to “foster the economic and social well-being of local communities within the area of outstanding natural beauty”, does not believe that the High Speed Rail proposal meets either of these criteria” \n -Environmental Law Foundation – High Speed Rail Briefing May 2010 \nhttp://www.elflaw.org/wp-content/themes/elftemplate/media/ELF-Briefing-High-Speed-Rail-Network-May-2010.pdf\n)\n \n“AONB’s have equivalent status to National Parks as far as conservation is concerned.  The single purpose of AONB designation is to conserve and enhance the natural beauty of the area”\n - HS2 Technical Appraisal \nhttp://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20110131042819/http://www.dft.gov.uk/pgr/rail/pi/highspeedrail/hs2ltd/technicalappendix/pdf/report.pdf\n \n \n“A lot of the \ntunnelling\n will be done in order to reduce the devastation that would otherwise arise in areas of outstanding natural beauty”\n - \nThe Minister of State, Department for Transport, Mr. \nSadiq\n Khan, Column 458, House of Commons debate 11\nth\n March 2010 \nhttp://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200910/cmhansrd/cm100311/debtext/100311-0008.htm\n \n \n“\nThe treatment of impacts that cannot be \nmonetised\n, such as those on landscapes, heritage and habitats, has been particularly limited in HS2’s business case, with very limited weight given to them” – \nRight Lines Charter, CPRE and others 2011 \nhttp://www.cpre.org.uk/what-we-do/transport/rail/update/item/1683-a-charter-for-high-speed-rail\n \nThe Chilterns Conservation Board calculate that HS2 will generate 1.7 million lorry journeys along local roads just to dispose of spoil – a lorry using local roads every 26 seconds every working day for 5 years - \nhttp://www.chilternsaonb.org/uploads/files/high_speed_2/Summary_of_case_against_HS2.pdf\n \n \nBucks Free Press 19\nth\n September 2013 \nhttp://www.bucksfreepress.co.uk/news/10681884.HS2_tunnel_spoil_to_be_dumped_in_Chilterns_AONB/\n \n \n“Initial HS2 assumption of 400kph – Group felt that 400kph unlikely to be affordable with adverse environmental impacts” – \nHS2 Ltd. Minutes of Technical Challenge Group 29th April 2009\n \n“A new high speed line would cost 9% more than a conventional railway,”\n Para 49 Strategic Case for HS2\n \n(\nAn alignment)\n “\nin parallel with an existing motorway …  made constructing the line 15% cheaper than it would have been otherwise.” \n - \nDr.Ing\n. \nEberhard\n \nJaensch\n, Network Strategy Unit, DB \nNetz\n AG, Railway Technical Review 2/05\n \nHS2 Ltd technical specification – minimum desirable radius of curvature 200kph = 1800m, 300kph = 4050m, 400kph = 7200m \nhttp://www.hs2.org.uk/assets/x/77048\n \n“For London to Birmingham, for example, operating at 360km/h as opposed to 300km/h would save just 3.5 minutes but consume 23% more energy”\n – Getting Back on Track, CPRE February 2011 \nwww.cpre.org.uk/resources/transport/rail/item/download/379\n \n \n“The UK is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by at least 80% by 2050, relative to 1990 levels” –\n \nDepartment of Energy and Climate Change\n \nhttp://www.decc.gov.uk/en/content/cms/tackling/2050/2050.aspx\n \n“Demand reductions across all sectors of the economy will be essential” - \nGenerating the Future, UK Energy Systems Fit for 2050, The Royal Academy of Engineering March 2010 \nhttp://www.raeng.org.uk/news/publications/list/reports/Generating_the_future_report.pdf\n \n \n“Work was underway to assess balance between power consumption and speed”\n – \nHS2 Ltd. Minutes of Technical Challenge Group 29th April 2009\n \n“The biggest issue in increasing \nShinkansen\n [high speed train] speed is noise control”\n-\n \nEast Japan Railway Company Technical Review Summer 2008\n \nhttp://www.jreast.co.jp/e/development/tech/contents12.html\n \n \n“Telling the People’s Daily that speed restrictions would be placed on the trains to make them most cost-efficient, \nSheng\n \nGuangzu\n, head of China’s railways ministry, said that trains running at 350 \nkph\n consume twice as much energy as those traveling at 200 \nkph\n. Slowing them up will save both on power costs and maintenance. Speeds are to be cut back from upwards of 350 \nkph\n to 200 kph-250 \nkph\n with a maximum of 300 \nkph\n” - \nhttp://chinabystander.wordpress.com/2011/04/14/slow-train-coming/\n \nPara 5.4.25 \nStrategic Case for HS2\n \nRoute Templates, drawing no. HS2_ARP_00_G1_RW_00148 \nhttp://assets.hs2.org.uk/sites/default/files/foi10-142redacted.pdf\n \n \nPara 6.34, High Speed Rail Command Paper, \nDfT\n March 2010\n \nhttp://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/+/http:/www.dft.gov.uk/pgr/rail/pi/highspeedrail/commandpaper/pdf/cmdpaper.pdf\n \n \n“For the purposes of our benefit-cost analysis, it is easier to measure and value some impacts than others. Some environmental impacts such as noise, carbon and air quality are captured in the benefit-cost ratio and our estimates have been updated in the latest analysis. Other effects such as the visual intrusion of infrastructure on landscape, and impacts on our heritage, are much harder to express in monetary terms” - Para 5.4.26 Strategic Case for HS2\n \nPara 5.4.41 Strategic Case for HS2\n \nFares on Long Distance Rail and HS2 London to West Midlands, \nDfT\n Factsheet 2011 -\nhttp://highspeedrail.dft.gov.uk/library/factsheets\n \n”Research from the Institute of Transport Studies suggests that for journey  time changes between 0 and 6 minutes, the value of time is more or less zero” – \nSecond Response to the Heathrow Airport High Speed Rail Access Review, British Airways, June 2010 \nhttp://www.scribd.com/doc/39878497/British-Airways-plc-–-Second-response-to-the-Heathrow-Airport-High-Speed-Rail-Access-Review\n \n \nDelivering a Sustainable Railway, \nDfT\n July 2007 \nhttp://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/+/http://www.dft.gov.uk/about/strategy/whitepapers/whitepapercm7176/multideliversustainrailway\n \n \nhttp://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/+/http://www.dft.gov.uk/about/strategy/whitepapers/whitepapercm7176/railwhitepaperresearch/evidencepackpassenger1/Page_040.ppt\n \n \nhttp://stophs2.org/news/7986-dfts-hidden-document\n \n \n“60% of surveyed business passengers said that they would not do any work in the time saved - a reduction in scheduled journey time by, for example 10 minutes, would increase the average amount of time spent working by all business rail passengers by just 0.75 minutes” \n- Productive Use of Rail Travel Time and the Valuation of Travel Time Savings for Rail Business Travellers, Final Report, \nDfT\n June 2009 \nhttp://assets.dft.gov.uk/publications/productive-use-of-travel-time/productive-use-of-travel-time.pdf\n \n \n“Evidence suggested that the benefits of further improving journey times beneath a 60 minute threshold were marginal \n(and)\n if the line was to be engineered for 300kph or faster, it may nonetheless not be too damaging \n(to the business case) \nif in places the line operated at a slightly lower speed”\n - HS2 \nStrategic Challenge Group meeting 23\nrd\n April 2009 \nhttp://www.hs2.org.uk/sites/default/files/inserts/Strategic%20Challenge%20Panel%20230409.pdf\n \n \n“The maximum speed of trains running on HS2 in the early years of operation will be 360km/h (225mph), with the majority of trains timetabled to run at 330km/h (206mph)”\n – Tim Smart, Head of Engineering and Operations, HS2 Ltd, The Engineer 5\nth\n August 2013\nhttp://www.theengineer.co.uk/civil-and-structural/in-depth/your-questions-answered-high-speed-2/1016870.article#ixzz2kqQhUrLS\n \nSection 4.2, Track - HS2 Project Specification, HS2 Ltd January 2012 \nhttp://assets.hs2.org.uk/sites/default/files/inserts/hs2%20project%20specification_january%202012.pdf\n \n \nSection 2.1, Overview – Chilterns Long Tunnel Options Review, Arup January 2012 \nhttp://assets.hs2.org.uk/sites/default/files/inserts/120116%20arup%20hs2%20lwm%20chiltern%20long%20tunnel%20options%20review%20report.pdf\n \n \n“Reducing the tunnel internal diameter to 9.2m which, for this length of tunnel, would have significant cost, \nprogramme\n and environmental benefits (in terms of spoil volumes and associated numbers of lorry movements)”\n – Section 3.2 Aerodynamics, \nChilterns Long Tunnel Options Review, Arup January 2012\n \nFor details, please see Heathrow Hub Ltd’s submissions to the Transport Select Committee’s Inquiry into High Speed Rail, \nEv\n w404,Ev w423 \nhttp://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201012/cmselect/cmtran/1185/1185ii.pdf\n \n \nPara 7.7, High Speed Rail Command Paper, March 2010 \nhttp://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/+/http:/www.dft.gov.uk/pgr/rail/pi/highspeedrail/commandpaper/pdf/cmdpaper.pdf\n \n \n“\nAround 22.5 miles (not including the HS1 link) would be in tunnel or green tunnel”\n – Para 2.1 \nSummary of effects of HS2 London to West Midlands route refinements, HS2 Ltd January 2012 \nhttps://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/3652/hs2-effects-of-route-refinements.pdf\n \n \nHS2 Press Release 23\nrd\n April 2013 \nhttp://assets.hs2.org.uk/sites/default/files/130419%20Northolt%20tunnel%20press%20notice%20FINAL.pdf\n \nand\n Safeguarding Directions 24\nth\n October 2013, \nDfT\n \nhttps://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/hs2-design-refinement-consultation\n. \n \n“\nThe noise from the M20 went a long way to disguise the noise from the rail line and the impacts were seen to be less where the line was placed in an existing blight corridor”\n – Transport for Buckinghamshire site visit to HS1, 30\nth\n July 2010 \nhttp://www.transportforbucks.net/Uploads/Files/hs2_hs1_visit.pdf\n \nThe Chilterns Conservation Board calculate that HS2 will generate 1.7 million lorry journeys along local roads just to dispose of spoil – a lorry using local roads every 26 seconds every working day for 5 years - \nhttp://www.chilternsaonb.org/uploads/files/high_speed_2/Summary_of_case_against_HS2.pdf\n \n \nGuidance Document 01, Airports Commission February 2013 \nhttps://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/70285/submitting-evidence-airports-commission.pdf\n \nArup submission to HS2 Ltd, December 2009 \nhttp://www.arup.com/News/2010_04_April/~/media/Files/PDF/News_and_Press/2010_04_April/091210_Arup_submission_to_HS2_Ltd_Full_Report_c_ARUP.ashx\n \n \n“\nComparing the ratio of long-haul seats flown relative to GDP of the city, Charles de Gaulle flies 81 long haul seats per million EUR of Paris GDP. Heathrow flies only 68 long haul seats per million EUR of London GDP. If Heathrow could achieve a similar seat to GDP ratio, this would imply 31 million long haul seats out of Heathrow each year instead of 26 million; an uplift of 18%”\n - \nConnecting for Growth, Frontier Economics September 2011 \nhttp://www.frontier-economics.com/_library/pdfs/Connecting%20for%20growth.pdf\n \n \n \n“\nThe High Speed Rail Line (HS2) to Birmingham may have to be adapted depending on what is decided about the future hub airport. A Bill for the line will take until 2015, the year the Davies Commission reports. I hope if anything needs to be adapted we will have the time to do it” - \nThe \nRt\n Hon Patrick \nMcLoughlin\n MP, Secretary of State, Department for Transport, Evening Standard interview 27\nth\n September 2012 \nhttp://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/i-wasnt-made-transport-secretary-to-push-through-third-runway-at-heathrowall-options-are-on-the-table-8181588.html\n \n \n“\nMaria Eagle\n: To ask the Secretary of State for Transport whether any changes have been made on expenditure on High Speed 2 since the figures set out in the 2010 spending review. [146109]\nMr\n Simon Burns:\n As part of the Government's comprehensive spending review in 2010, £773 million was allocated to the development of the High Speed 2 Project. This has increased to around £900 million, primarily due to an increase in the capital budget relating to property compensation. This increase reflects the forthcoming introduction, subject to the outcome of the recent consultation, of long-term discretionary and statutory compensation schemes for Phase One. The increase in budget was notified to HM Treasury as part of the Department's main estimate submissions at the beginning of\n \n2012”\n – Written Questions 6\nth\n March 2013, \nhttp://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm130306/text/130306w0001.htm\n \n  \n“\nLabour\n would delay construction of the London leg of the HS2 railway in order to redesign the route through the capital, shadow transport secretary Maria Eagle has told City A.M”\n - City AM, 27\nth\n August \n 2013 \nhttp://www.cityam.com/article/1377573343/exclusive-labour-threatens-redesign-hs2-link\n \n \n“\nThe proposals for a HS1 -H52 link remain unacceptable in light of restrictions on future development on the North London Line; we would call on the Government to re-examine proposals for a \ntunnelled\n connection which could enable operators to make use of Stratford International”\n - \nLondon Assembly response to HS2 Design Refinement Consultation, 11\nth\n July 2013 \nhttp://www.london.gov.uk/sites/default/files/HS2%20consultation%20response%20letter%20to%20Rt%20Hon%20Patrick%20McLoughlin_0.pdf\n \n \n“\nThe Mayor has asked the Secretary of State to consider alternative options for linking HS2 to HS1 that would avoid conflicts with the North London Line”\n – Update on HS2 to Environment, Corporate and Planning Panel, 23\nrd\n February 2012 Transport for London \nhttp://www.tfl.gov.uk/assets/downloads/Item04-High-Speed-2-Update.pdf\n \n \nCrossrail\n 2: Supporting London’s Growth, London First February 2013 \nhttp://londonfirst.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/LF_ an2_REPORT_AW_Single_Pages.pdf\n \n \nAn assessment of HS2’s immediate cost to the people,\n \ncommunities and businesses based in the London Borough\n \nof Camden\n, London Borough of Camden July 2013 \nhttps://www.camden.gov.uk/ccm/navigation/environment/planning-and-built-environment/major-developments/high-speed-2/;jsessionid=B49F4B0922D81EE9AACC2F9B5E46D438\n \n \n“\nThe Department has forecast that phase one will result in reduced operating costs on the existing network of £3.0 billion (discounted) over 60 years. This saving is estimated on the assumption that fewer long-distance services are likely to run on the West Coast Main Line when phase one is in operation” - \nPara 3.7 National Audit Office \nhttp://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Full-Report.pdf\n \n \n“The Department's aim is that all towns or cities which currently have a direct service to London will retain broadly comparable or better services once HS2 is completed” \n– Written answer, 18\nth\n November 2013 \nhttp://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmhansrd/cm131118/text/131118w0005.htm#1311199001465\n \n"